essary randomness data.\n\nNow I'm setting up the account files and bootstrap flags to pre-populate these PDAs with the required data...\n\nActually, I'm realizing this approach requires computing Solana addresses in a bash script, which isn't straightforward without Node.js. Maybe I should create a Node.js helper script that generates the addresses and JSON files, then have the bootstrap call it.\n\nBut stepping back, I'm wondering if there's a simpler path here. What if the lifecycle test just creates the match through the UI, then joins and resolves it programmatically using mock Orao accounts? That way I can bypass the address computation complexity and focus on testing the actual flow—Player A creates through the UI, Player B joins programmatically with mocked randomness, and then claims work correctly.\n\nLooking at the bootstrap script more carefully, I can use `solana-test-validator --account` to pre-load account state from JSON files. The account JSON format needs lamports and data fields...\n\nGenerating account JSON files... base64_encoded_data\", \"base64\"],\n  \"owner\": \"program_id\",\n  \"executable\": false,\n  \"rentEpoch\": 0\n}\n```\n\nOK so here's my practical plan:\n\n1. Create a Node.js helper script (or TypeScript) that:\n   - Computes all required PDA addresses\n   - Generates JSON account files for the Orao mock accounts\n   - These are placed in a temp directory\n\n2. Modify the bootstrap script to:\n   - Run the helper script first\n   - Add `--account` flags for each generated file\n\n3. Create the lifecycle test that:\n   - Player A creates match through UI\n   - Player B joins through UI (now works because Orao state exists)\n   - Since the randomness is pre-fulfilled at genesis, the match resolves immediately after the join\n   - Both players see the result in the UI\n   - Winner claims through UI\n\nThe key insight is that since Player A is deterministic, I can pre-compute both the match PDA and the derived orao_random PDA ahead of time. This works perfectly as long as Player A always creates the match, which is guaranteed by the test design. The frontend will detect fulfillment once the randomness data has non-zero bytes at the expected offset.\n\nRather than getting stuck on the exact data layout details, I should just start implementing and debug as issues surface. Let me check the mock VRF code to understand the exact account structure I need to generate.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11251,"cache_read_input_tokens":66957,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11251},"output_tokens":15,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b0a0dcb3-1758-4eec-aea3-903a9f33143b","uuid":"7bc0aa5c-7b0d-449c-8675-df1099edec03"}
